<TEXT>
more and more economists are expressing 
pessimism about the chances of surviving another year without a 
recession as fears over rising inflation and tightcredit policies 
continue to mount 
some analysts are even raising the spectre of the old bugaboo of 
the 1970s stagflation a period when growth slows and unemployment 
climbs but inflation rises as well 
for its part the bush administration is continuing to insist 
that the economy is on track for a soft landing in which growth 
slows enough to dampen inflationary pressures but not enough to 
push the country into a recession 
but private economists are not so sure the latest survey of 50 
top economists issued each month by blue chip economic indicators 
an investment newsletter showed that more than half of the panel 
now expect a recession to begin by late this year or early next 
year 
even those analysts who are not predicting an outright 
recession defined as two consecutive quarters of negative growth 
are looking for this year to be extremely sluggish 
the governments first look at how the overall economy is 
performing will be issued on wednesday and despite all the 
pessimism the number is expected to be very good on paper at 
least 
many forecasters believe the gross national product the total 
output of goods and services expanded at an annual rate of 5 
percent in the januarymarch quarter 
that would represent the fastest rate of growth in more than a 
year and would be double the 24 percent gnp rate turned in during 
the final three months of 1988 
the trouble is that all of the pickup in growth will result from 
an artificial calculation needed to close out the books on last 
summers devastating drought 
while the droughts primary impact on the economy occurred in 
the second and third quarters last year the commerce department 
annualized its figures to show the lost farm output for the entire 
year now with a new year there will be an artificial bounceback 
in the numbers 
discounting this factor economic growth is expected to have 
slowed dramatically in the first three months of this year to 
around 25 percent down a full percentage point from the 35 
percent nonfarm growth in the fourth quarter 
early statistics showing sluggish retail sales and plunging 
housing construction in april have bolstered the belief that the 
economy will slow even further in the current apriljune quarter 
cynthia latta an economist with data resources inc of 
lexington mass said gnp growth would likely fall below 2 percent 
in the current quarter and average a weak 1 percent rate in the 
second half of the year 
an economy growing at such sluggish rates would not be able to 
generate enough new jobs to keep the unemployment rate from rising 
ms latta said dri is forecasting that unemployment will climb 
to 56 percent by the end of the year up from the current 15year 
low of 5 percent 
ms latta said she is not forecasting a recession because she 
believes the federal reserve will be successful in its yearlong 
effort to tighten credit enough to dampen demand but not enough to 
push the country into a slump 
we believe the odds still favor a soft landing the slowdown 
has been fairly broadly distributed and there is not a sign that 
any one sector is going to collapse she said 
michael evans head of a washington forecasting firm said he 
too believed the country would be able to escape without a 
recession over the next year as long as business profits do not 
begin to suffer from escalating wage demands or rising costs for 
raw materials 
we dont really get recessions until businesses get nervous 
and start cutting back he said i dont see signs that is 
happening 
but allen sinai chief economist of the boston co is 
predicting a recession beginning early next year 
i side with history he said the fed is making a mighty 
effort to engineer a soft landing for the economy but in the past 
they have failed more often they have succeeded 
some analysts believe the bush administration would be wise to 
take a downturn now as far away from the next presidential 
election as possible just as ronald reagan did in his first term 
when the country suffered through the 198182 recession 
but administration officials who are counting on robust 
economic growth to meet the goal of lowering the federal budget 
deficit below 100 billion next year continue to insist that they 
see no signs of a downturn 
michael boskin chairman of the presidents council of economic 
advisers said in recent congressional testimony that he remained 
optimistic that the current economic expansion would be able to 
continue for some time to come as long as policy makers avoid 
mistakes such as increasing taxes to balance the budget 
