<TEXT>
an international team of scientists will take 
to the ocean in may to study the role played by sulfur gases in 
changing the earths climate 
researchers from the united states and the soviet union will 
take part in the study focusing on sulfur gases released from the 
water in the eastern pacific ocean the national oceanic and 
atmospheric administration said today 
sulfur gases are oxidized in the air and the resulting chemicals 
are thought to influence the reflectivity of clouds in the sky 
according to dr timothy bates of noaas pacific marine 
environmental laboratory in seattle 
scientists are trying to determine the overall effect of clouds 
in climate that is because clouds reflect some of the energy from 
the sun back into space but at the same time they trap some of the 
heat the earth itself would radiate away the balance of heat 
trapped and that reflected varies with the reflectivity of the 
clouds 
the 12day research trip aboard the noaa ship mcarthur will 
allow the scientists to measure the sulfur and nitrogen particles 
in the air and better calculate their influence on clouds 
at the same time measurements of clouds themselves will be made 
by aircraft from the national aeronautics and space administration 
the university of washington and battelle pacific northwest 
laboratories 
other research organizations participating in the study include 
the national science foundation department of defense department 
of energy monterey bay aquarium research institute university of 
arizona georgia institute of technology university of miami the 
soviet institute of atmospheric physics and the soviet institute of 
applied geophysics 
