<TEXT>
the supreme court today left intact a 101 
million refund the nations telephone companies were ordered to pay 
customers for excessive charges in 1978 
the court without comment rejected arguments that the federal 
communications commission overstepped its authority in ordering the 
refunds 
the commission in 1976 allowed american telephone amp telegraph 
co to set phone rates designed to yield a rate of return of up to 
10 percent a year 
atampts earnings in 1978 exceeded the 10 percent figure by 101 
million the commission ruled in 1984 
by that year atampt had divested itself of its regional operating 
companies in settling a federal antitrust lawsuit 
the commission therefore ordered the regional companies to 
reduce their phone rates so their customers would receive the 101 
million refund 
the us circuit court of appeals here in a 21 ruling in 1987 
upheld the commissions orders the appeals court rejected 
arguments that the reduced rates are a retroactive refund in 
violation of federal law 
the telephone companies also said ordering refunds is unfair 
because atampts rate of return in 1976 was only 925 percent yet 
the phone companies were not permitted to raise customer rates to 
make up the shortfall 
the appeals court said the rate of return approved by the 
commission is not designed to assure a certain minimum level of 
earnings for the companies each year 
the companies are entitled only to earn an overall reasonable 
return the appeals court said the commission has concluded 
that a guaranteed minimum annual return is not essential to protect 
that right that conclusion is a reasonable one 
in addition the appeals court upheld the commissions decision 
that the companies also refund interest earned on the 101 million 
we perceive no inequity in requiring the companies to pay 
full interest on earnings they had no right to retain in the first 
place the appeals court said 
the communications satellite corp comsat supported the phone 
companies position the satellite communications company was 
ordered by the commission last year to refund 388 million to its 
customers 
the cases are southern bell vs fcc 881249 and new england 
telephone vs fcc 881250 
