the supreme court today agreed to review a 
judges order raising property taxes to help pay for racially 
desegregating public schools in kansas city mo 
the justices said they will hear arguments that the judge 
overstepped his authority when imposing the tax hike for all 
property within the citys school district 
a series of orders by us district judge russell g clark that 
would cost hundreds of millions of dollars to implement was 
challenged in appeals by state and county officials and school 
district taxpayers 
most of the judges orders were upheld by the 8th us circuit 
court of appeals last aug 19 
the funding controversy dates back to a 1977 lawsuit seeking to 
correct the physical decline of predominantly black schools in 
kansas city 
before 1954 missouri law required schools to be racially 
segregated from 1954 to 1984 the percentage of black students in 
kansas citys school district climbed from 225 percent to 677 
percent 
in a 1987 ruling clark found that the city school districts 
physical facilities have literally rotted and ordered the 
state and school district to upgrade them 
in upholding most of the judges order the 8th circuit court 
said there are still vestiges of the dual school system 
lingering in the city school district and the district and the 
state have not met their obligations to disestablish that system 
the judges orders called for two major remedies 
a magnet school plan providing that by the 199192 school 
year every high school and middle school in the city and about 
half the elementary schools will feature distinctive themes such 
as foreign languages performing arts or math and science 
a capital improvements program costing some 260 million to be 
completed by the fall of 1990 
to enable the city school district to pay its share of the 
desegregation plans costs the judge imposed a 15 percent income 
tax surcharge and hiked school district property taxes to 4 per 
100 assessed valuation through the 199192 fiscal year 
the states appeal granted review today says the 4 per 100 
levy represented a doubling of the local property tax 
clark ordered the tax increases because no money was available 
to finance the construction of new schools between 1970 and 1983 
school district voters had turned down six proposals to increase 
taxes for education 
he also authorized the school district to issue 150 million in 
20year capital improvement bonds 
the appeals court upheld the property tax hike but struck down 
the income tax surcharge which had raised some 30 million before 
being invalidated 
the state was ordered to pay 75 percent of the desegregation 
costs the school district the remaining 25 percent 
the state appeal acted on today said the lower court rulings 
rest upon an unwarranted extension of this courts desegregation 
cases 
the appeal said the magnet school remedy was as ordered by 
clark overbroad unlike any ever ordered by a federal court 
the appeal also said that the order imposing a tax increase is 
outside the bounds of judicial authority 
in a brief order the justices rejected two appeals filed in the 
case and limited review of the states appeal to the validity of 
the ordered tax increase 
the cases are missouri vs jenkins 881150 clark vs jenkins 
881194 and jackson county vs jenkins 881228 
</TEXT>
