whaling supporters welcomed home the mother ship of 
japans whaling fleet today after a fourmonth hunt in the 
antarctic in which it dodged protesters and killed 241 whales 
the nisshin maru no 3s return marked the end of the second 
year of japans research whaling program which it launched after 
officially ending commercial whaling in 1987 to comply with a ban 
imposed by the international whaling commission 
in a welcoming ceremony on the ships long rusted deck 
officials promised the 120 crew members they would seek an end to 
the ban which is to be reevaluated in 1990 
i understand that you had many difficulties on your voyage 
fukujiro kikuchi a parliament member told the crew were doing 
our best in the hope that sometime somewhere japan will be able to 
resume commercial whaling 
below the 23000ton ships deck were 241 minke whales already 
prepared into meat in the vessels processing plant 
when japanese whaling was at its peak in the early 1960s whales 
provided 23 percent of all meat consumed in the country declining 
supplies since then have turned whale meat into a delicacy but 
japan is still the worlds largest consumer of whale flesh 
under the international whaling commission charter member 
nations may conduct research whaling at any time without permission 
from the commission and then use the meat japan says it hopes to 
show through its research that some whale species are plentiful 
enough to allow a resumption of limited commercial whaling 
estimates of the current number of minkes a smaller species 
range from 400000 to 700000 
but international environmental groups such as greenpeace have 
charged that japan is using the research provision as a ploy to 
continue whaling and that nonlethal research methods are 
available 
greenpeace members used a ship and rubber rafts to try to block 
the nisshin maru and its three catcher boats during their hunt in 
the antarctic and had one minor collision with the mother ship 
hidehiro kato director of research on board the nisshin maru 
said the voyage had shown that the random sampling methods used in 
the research could be applied to a broader research program 
id prefer to use nonlethal methods but they arent able to 
tell us age reproductive status or condition of the whales he 
said at this point the best approach is a combination of lethal 
and nonlethal research 
japanese officials have said at least 825 whales must be caught 
each season to make the research program scientifically accurate 
but because of strong international opposition they reduced this 
years goal to 300 
kato said bad weather was primarily responsible for the fleets 
