<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether the government may tax as income the deposits that utility 
companies demand from customers to insure payment of future bills 
the court said it will hear a bush administration appeal in a 
case involving an indiana electric utility 
administration officials said a considerable amount of money 
could be at stake the internal revenue service estimated that more 
than 150 such cases involving over 300 million in potential taxes 
are pending in the courts or before the irs 
the case acted on today stems from a deposit policy of the 
indianapolis power and light co 
the policy as amended in 1976 required some electricity 
customers to deposit up to twice their estimated monthly bills with 
the company 
the company required the deposits from new customers whose 
creditworthiness was in doubt and from existing customers with a 
record of late payment of their bills 
the utility paid 6 percent annual interest on the deposits to 
customers if it held the money for at least a year the deposit was 
refunded if the customer met a credit test or if the customers 
bill was paid on time for nine straight months or for 10 out of 12 
months 
the 7th us circuit court of appeals last september upheld a 
ruling by the us tax court that the deposits were not a form of 
advance payment and thus the utility did not have to pay federal 
income tax on them 
the appeals court accepted the tax courts interpretation that 
the money was meant as security for the utility not advance 
payment of a customers bill 
justice department lawyers in urging the high court to overturn 
the 7th circuit court ruling noted that another federal appeals 
court has ruled the opposite way the governments appeal urged the 
justices to resolve the conflict 
the case is commissioner of irs vs indianapolis power 881319 
</TEXT>
