<TEXT>
social scientists are debating what turns english 
soccer fans into tribal mobs as a shattered nation buries its dead 
from the sheffield stadium tragedy and awaits its share of the 
blame for an earlier disaster 
researchers are trying to explain why soccer stadiums become 
breeding grounds for racism and violence and why bluecollar males 
are attracted to hooliganism the way youngsters in los angeles are 
drawn to innercity gangs 
they also are exploring why many young fans shun the comfort of 
seated areas and choose to stand for hours on a cold crowded 
concrete terrace the scene of the april 15 crush that killed 95 
liverpool fans in sheffield 
days after that tragedy england is readying itself for another 
reminder of the stains on its image of polished civility a belgian 
judge will issue his verdict friday in the case of 26 liverpool 
fans accused of causing the 1985 heysel stadium riot in which 39 
people died 
the sheffield disaster was caused less by outright hooliganism 
than by overcrowding but it quickened the debate on such questions 
as what causes a crowd to become belligerent or to stampede 
whether the game itself is to blame and whether outdated stadiums 
turn people into animals 
violence by sports fans is not new chariot race hooligans 
caused a riot in sixth century rome that reputedly led to 30000 
deaths 
today political scientists are focusing on the unequal 
distribution of wealth and jobs in england particularly in 
industrial cities such as liverpool and the role that class 
distinctions play in treatment of crowds 
commentators are accusing the soccer establishment of showing 
contempt for fans by providing inadequate facilities and neglecting 
safety 
social scientists are concentrating on human behavior and the 
way it reacts to the environment they point to degrading 
conditions on the terraces of 19thcentury stadiums in which 
comfort and sanitation are ignored 
the more you treat them like animals the more its likely to 
be a selffulfilling prophecy said criminologist eugene 
trivizas a specialist in hooligan behavior 
psychologist david canter accuses clubs of almost literally 
getting away with murder for the last 10 years or so by skimping 
on stadium facilities 
despite the discomfort on the terraces researchers say young 
urban males prefer the shared ordeal of packing together like 
sardines because it offers them anonymity and a sense of power 
young males in urban populations lack any kind of group 
identity and this is what football soccer gives them said 
desmond morris author of popular anthropological studies like 
the naked ape 
it offers them a chance to belong to a group and express their 
joys and fears through that group young males need to express 
themselves in some way that involves risktaking and honor he 
said in an interview 
bolstered by alcohol and machismo they press their bodies 
against one another and sway to team songs just as their fathers 
and grandfathers did they yell racial epithets at players crude 
insults at women 
working classes are less likely to express emotion in subtle 
verbal forms said canter whose book football in its place 
is to be published in may its more likely to be some sort of 
physical representation such as jumping up and down and shouting 
trivizas said absorption in a crowd dismisses personal 
inhibitions because fans believe it is difficult to be held 
responsible or to be identified if they misbehave 
there is an impression of universality if other people are 
doing what you are doing then you think what youre doing cannot 
be wrong people think they can behave with relative impunity 
in his 1981 book the soccer tribe morris likened soccer 
fans to religious zealots and warned that the tribal element could 
be eradicated by forcing fans to sit comfortably and quietly in 
stadiums and turning this symbolic event into disneyland fun 
perhaps the greatest dilemma facing the soccer tribe today is 
the question of whether its main activity is a sacred ritual or a 
social entertainment he wrote should the ancient traditions 
of spartan suffering give way to theater comforts and modern 
razzmatazz 
 
