<TEXT>
nearly a third of those needing heart 
transplants eventually may be candidates for new surgery in which a 
flap of back muscle is wrapped around the ailing heart to help it 
pump doctors said monday 
the candidates ideally will be people who are heading toward 
a heart transplant but still have enough reserve left said dr 
george magovern chairman of surgery at allegheny general hospital 
the experimental procedure was performed last month using a 
special pacemaker that stimulates the transplanted back muscle in 
multiple bursts unlike conventional singlepulse pacemakers the 
muscle is thus able to contract with the heart over longer periods 
of time 
it was the first time the 3ounce cardiomyostimulator 
manufactured by medtronic inc of minneapolis had been implanted 
into a patient in the united states magovern said allegheny 
general is the only hospital with us food and drug administration 
approval to use the device in clinical trials 
the patient ralph beilstein 57 an interior decorator from 
nearby sewickley said he feels marvelous he had suffered from 
chronic heart failure since 1964 
his left latissimus dorsi muscle was partially removed march 20 
and wrapped around his heart three days later the pacemaker was 
implanted during the march 23 operation below the left side of his 
rib cage and turned on march 31 he was discharged wednesday 
i just generally feel better psychologically as well as 
physically beilstein said at a hospital news conference attended 
by his wife virginia and their four daughters and eight 
grandchildren 
he was able to avoid a heart transplant a riskier procedure 
that can involve lengthy waits because of the scarcity of donor 
organs 
the muscleflap operation was first performed in the united 
states by magovern in 1985 the procedure had been performed only 
once before about six months earlier in paris 
by jan 1 the muscleflap operation had been performed about 40 
times around the world six of them at allegheny general said dr 
ignacio christlieb who assisted in beilsteins operation 
the cardiomyostimulator was used in about threequarters of the 
cases all overseas 
in each case doctors detach the left latissimus dorsi muscle 
from the patients back except for a small portion remaining 
attached by an artery and nerve under the arm about 2 inches of 
one rib is removed and the muscle flap is pushed through and 
wrapped around the heart 
a 1footlong wire woven through the muscle flap is attached to 
the implanted pacemaker which is run by a lithium battery 
one system of insulated wires sends signals from the heart to 
the pacemaker another sends signals to electrodes in the muscle 
flap enabling the muscle to beat in tandem with the heart 
skeletal muscle such as the latissimus dorsi lacks the natural 
electrical conduction system of heart muscle and therefore requires 
a precisely timed and controlled burst of pulses to stimulate 
contraction 
beilstein said he is not limited physically as a result of his 
removed muscle the muscle has been removed and used in the past in 
breast reconstruction and repairing leg fractures 
its a muscle the body can spare heckler said 
doctors say theyre not sure how long the muscle will be able to 
function around the heart 
its like youre training an athlete to perform a given 
task christlieb said if you take that training continuously 
the nutrition is good and theres no additional disease it back 
muscle could go on for a lifetime 
what we dont know for sure is which is the ideal electric 
current to do this and thats part of our ongoing 
investigations he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

