<TEXT>
advocates for the homeless have accused the 
bush administration of violating a federal court order to make 
surplus government property available for the homeless 
the national coalition for the homeless filed a motion late 
friday with us district judge oliver gasch in washington charging 
that the department of health and human services is refusing to 
accept or process applications for properties the coalition 
contends are suitable for the homeless hhs was designated as the 
agency to process the applications the coalition said 
gasch ruled in a suit by the group last december that the 
federal government must review hundreds of surplus federal 
properties across the country for possible use by the homeless 
the coalition contends that under the 1987 mckinney homeless 
assistance act passed by congress properties determined suitable 
by the department of housing and urban development must be made 
available to states local governments and nonprofit groups to use 
as facilities to shelter or assist the homeless 
