the army said monday it had grounded its 
entire fleet of vietnam era uh1 huey transport helicopters for a 
safety inspection of main rotor bolts 
the service in a statement said the grounding order was issued 
late friday and was keeping about 3100 choppers on the ground 
lt col john reitz an army spokesman said the grounding order 
was prompted by an incident last week in which a huey was being 
moved manually across a tarmac and two of the bolts in the main 
rotor pillow block suddenly snapped 
he said that further inspection showed cracks and stress 
corrosion in the bolts 
in this case there was no accident and no loss of life 
reitz said but you would have a big problem if this happened in 
flight so a grounding order was issued immediately to ensure 
safety 
the bolts at issue sit atop the main rotor hub and help hold the 
main rotor blades to the shaft 
according to reitz army aviation units are being advised the 
hueys can return to operation as soon as the onetime safety check 
of the bolts is conducted 
in all likelihood most of the fleet will be back up in the 
air very quickly he added 
the 3100 huey helicopters assigned to activeduty units include 
three variants of the chopper the basic uh1h transport a uh1v 
medevac variant and an eh1h electronic warfare variant the hueys 
are deployed with army units around the world 
the grounding order did not affect another variant of the 
chopper used exclusively by national guard units 
