<TEXT>
university of utah chemist b stanley pons 
said monday that he and british colleague martin fleischmann plan a 
new round of experiments to expand their research on 
roomtemperature nuclear fusion 
one experiment will be five times larger than the tabletop 
experiment the scientists used to produce what they claim is 
nuclear fusion 
pons declined to detail the new experiments but said he planned 
to begin up to 20 over the next two weeks to supplement the four 
currently operating 
among them will be tests of different metals than the palladium 
used in the original experiments and new designs for the apparatus 
pons and fleischmann have used electrically charged rods of 
palladium in a beaker of deuterium oxide which they said produced 
up to eight times the energy consumed 
i think this round of experiments will bring up a host of new 
data pons told reporters at a briefing before his departure for 
washington dc where he and fleischmann will address a 
congressional committee about their controversial experiments 
the larger experiment could be another step toward a practical 
application for the heat and therefore energy of fusion pons 
said 
he estimated it might take 20 years to design and build a pilot 
plant for usable fusion energy which scientists say would be 
cheaper and cleaner than the fission that currently fuels nuclear 
reactors 
pons and fleischmann stunned the scientific world march 23 when 
they announced the results of their experiment which was conducted 
in a university laboratory several laboratories around the united 
states and abroad have since claimed to duplicate or approximate 
the results although other experts remain skeptical 
university spokeswoman pam fogle said sunday the two researchers 
were asked to appear wednesday before the house science space and 
technology committee to discuss their fusion process and answer 
questions 
a congressional delegation also will visit the utah campus in 
midmay 
