<TEXT>
a soviet official said monday the soviet 
union plans to sign an accord that would allow its citizens to take 
human rights complaints to international investigators 
moscow will sign the optional protocol to the international 
covenant on civil and political rights later this year or early 
next year said the official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
accepting that pact would mean soviet citizens could appeal to 
the unaffiliated human rights committee in cases involving 
emigration torture forced labor arbitrary arrest or detention 
freedom of thought and conscience and peaceful assembly 
the official said the soviet government has been considering 
signing the pact for some time and various government ministries 
have been reviewing the effect it would have 
there is an intention he said 
some of the agencies studying the matter are the ministry of 
justice the public prosecutors office and the ministry of the 
interior he added 
soviet acceptance of the protocol would be a dramatic extension 
of president mikhail s gorbachevs declaration last december that 
human rights should be given new emphasis in international affairs 
in march the soviet union said it would accept the world courts 
jurisdiction in the international covenant on civil and political 
rights and five other human rights treaties that bar slavery 
prostitution torture and genocide and guarantee womens rights 
that decision reversed a soviet postworld war ii policy of 
resisting outside scrutiny of its practices 
however only governments can appeal to the world court at the 
hague 
when nations sign the optional protocol their citizens can file 
complaints with the human rights committee an international body 
of legal specialists with the power to order compensation 
hungary ratified the protocol last year joining 40 other 
nations 
of the six major human rights treaties the united states has 
ratified only one outlawing genocide and has not accepted world 
court authority in that treaty 
acceptance of the optional protocol should help the soviet 
effort to hold a human rights conference in moscow in 1991 as one 
of several followup meetings to the 1975 helsinki agreements on 
european security and cooperation 
</TEXT>
