<TEXT>
in the 1970s banks overflowed with money to 
lend and south americans were ready to borrow it today the south 
americans struggle just to pay the interest on the loans let alone 
the principal foreign debt is emptying south americas pocketbook 
this is another in a series of periodic reports by the associated 
press on the economic social and political turbulence that has 
turned south america into a continent in crisis 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
across south america the crushing burden of foreign debt piled 
up largely by military governments no longer in power is stifling 
economies stirring unrest in the masses and threatening fragile 
democracies 
some leaders see the crisis as an opening for radical populists 
with radical solutions debt moratoriums or outright repudiation 
of debt for example and in turn the possibility of military 
rule once more 
foreign debt is likely to be a major issue in presidential 
elections this year argentina brazil chile paraguay bolivia and 
uruguay 
compounding the debt problem however are factors that have 
pervaded south american nations long before they went on a 
borrowing binge mismanagement corruption and accumulations of 
vast wealth in cities while handtomouth poverty and illiteracy 
persisted in the countryside 
colombia and peru face the additional burdens of guerrilla wars 
and the illegal cocaine trade 
ten south american nations owe a total of 2774 billion 
according to compilations of the economic commission for latin 
america and repayments are taking a heavy toll on their economies 
and the livelihood of their peoples 
five years ago brazilians could buy a cookstove for what it 
costs them now to buy a kilo of black beans inflation has soared 
to 1000 percent yearly and the cruzado currency has been devalued 
by a factor of 1 million 
in colombia peru and bolivia efforts to cope with mounting 
debts have opened the way to a 10billion cocaine trade that feeds 
the starved economies with hard currency and provides jobs for the 
unemployed drug money threatens to erode accepted economic and 
political systems 
in argentina once one of the worlds wealthiest nations the 
80 billion gross domestic product has stagnated for a decade and 
the value of the austral currency steadily declines 
in venezuela where oil once brought wealth poverty is rising 
fast a survey of 23 million families in 1981 by the latin 
american institute of social research showed 22 percent were poor 
its survey of more than 3 million in 1987 showed the rate had risen 
to 54 percent three days of rioting over price increases in late 
february and early march left 276 people dead and more than 1000 
injured and conditions remain tense 
the riots were the result of a crisis that can be written in 
capital letters the foreign debt said carlos andres perez 
venezuelas president 
a debt paid with misery is a bill that will eventually be paid 
with democracy said president jose sarney of brazil which has 
the highest of the third worlds foreign debt 115 billion 
democracy is losing ground in latin america because the 
solutions it has presented do not attend national problems we 
offer pessimistic solutions and the parties of the left optimistic 
ones 
said argentinas president raul alfonsin the misery the 
depressing conditions of life the lack of food housing health 
training education and jobs create a culture dish that can be 
exploited by ultras and extremists of whatever tendency 
foreign debt has become increasingly politicized on the 
continent 
it is a top issue in the election campaigns in brazil and 
argentina where leftist or populist candidates are frontrunners 
they began entering the picture as governments cut wages and 
subsidies on basic goods and services to meet creditor demands for 
economic austerity the cuts resulted in sharply reduced living 
standards on top of stalled economic growth 
a plan announced in march by us treasury secretary nicholas 
brady acknowledges for the first time that the third worlds debt 
may not be payable 
though still sketchy bradys proposal to eliminate 20 percent 
of debt marks a distinct turn from the reagan administrations 
policy of piling new loans on old 
banks too now recognize that only debt relief will avoid 
explosive social unrest and guarantee at least partial payment 
voluntary debt reduction is a necessary part of any future 
debt strategy said william rhodes head of the citicorp 
debtrestructuring committee 
most south american governments have long cried for creditors to 
share responsibility for the lending bonanza of the 1970s when 
most of their debt was accrued by military governments without 
popular mandates 
they argue that banks flush with petrodollars from the 1973 oil 
crisis were looking for ways to invest latin american nations 
which were posting 4 to 5 percent growth rates and hadnt defaulted 
on a debt since the 1930s seemed a good prospect 
but many experts now say the banks took undue risks failing to 
verify how the money was spent and ignoring repayment 
possibilities money was lent at floating interest rates which in 
the 1970s were at a low of 1 percent 
though much of the borrowed money was used for important 
development projects such as roads airports and hydroelectric 
dams much more was wasted 
the brazilian military government spent an estimated 20 billion 
on a program to build 10 nuclear plants by 1980 but only one has 
been built a plant nicknamed lightening bug because it shuts 
down so often and parts for three others rust in warehouses 
</TEXT>
